 4598        /// <summary>
 4599        /// Registers the continuation and possibly runs it (if the task is already finished).
 4600        /// </summary>
 4601        /// <param name="continuationTask">The continuation task itself.</param>
 4602        /// <param name="scheduler">TaskScheduler with which to associate continuation task.</param>
 4603        /// <param name="options">Restrictions on when the continuation becomes active.</param>
 4604        internal void ContinueWithCore(Task continuationTask,
 4605                                       TaskScheduler scheduler,
 4606                                       CancellationToken cancellationToken,
 4607                                       TaskContinuationOptions options)
 4608        {
 4609            Contract.Requires(continuationTask != null, "Task.ContinueWithCore(): null continuationTask");
 4610            Contract.Requires(scheduler != null, "Task.ContinueWithCore(): null scheduler");
 4611            Contract.Requires(!continuationTask.IsCompleted, "Did not expect continuationTask to be completed");
 4612
 4613            // Create a TaskContinuation
 14614            TaskContinuation continuation = new StandardTaskContinuation(continuationTask, options, scheduler);
 4615
 4616            // If cancellationToken is cancellable, then assign it.
 14617             if (cancellationToken.CanBeCanceled)
 4618            {
 14619                 if (IsCompleted || cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
 4620                {
 4621                    // If the antecedent has completed, then we will not be queuing up
 4622                    // the continuation in the antecedent's continuation list.  Likewise,
 4623                    // if the cancellationToken has been canceled, continuationTask will
 4624                    // be completed in the AssignCancellationToken call below, and there
 4625                    // is no need to queue the continuation to the antecedent's continuation
 4626                    // list.  In either of these two cases, we will pass "null" for the antecedent,
 4627                    // meaning "the cancellation callback should not attempt to remove the
 4628                    // continuation from its antecedent's continuation list".
 14629                    continuationTask.AssignCancellationToken(cancellationToken, null, null);
 14630                }
 4631                else
 4632                {
 4633                    // The antecedent is not yet complete, so there is a pretty good chance
 4634                    // that the continuation will be queued up in the antecedent.  Assign the
 4635                    // cancellation token with information about the antecedent, so that the
 4636                    // continuation can be dequeued upon the signalling of the token.
 4637                    //
 4638                    // It's possible that the antecedent completes before the call to AddTaskContinuation,
 4639                    // and that is a benign race condition.  It just means that the cancellation will result in
 4640                    // a futile search of the antecedent's continuation list.
 14641                    continuationTask.AssignCancellationToken(cancellationToken, this, continuation);
 4642                }
 4643            }
 4644
 4645            // In the case of a pre-canceled token, continuationTask will have been completed
 4646            // in a Canceled state by now.  If such is the case, there is no need to go through
 4647            // the motions of queuing up the continuation for eventual execution.
 14648             if (!continuationTask.IsCompleted)
 4649            {
 4650                // We need additional correlation produced here to ensure that at least the continuation
 4651                // code will be correlatable to the currrent activity that initiated "this" task:
 4652                //  . when the antecendent ("this") is a promise we have very little control over where
 4653                //    the code for the promise will run (e.g. it can be a task from a user provided
 4654                //    TaskCompletionSource or from a classic Begin/End async operation); this user or
 4655                //    system code will likely not have stamped an activity id on the thread, so there's
 4656                //    generally no easy correlation that can be provided between the current activity
 4657                //    and the promise. Also the continuation code may run practically on any thread.
 4658                //    Since there may be no correlation between the current activity and the TCS's task
 4659                //    activity, we ensure we at least create a correlation from the current activity to
 4660                //    the continuation that runs when the promise completes.
 14661                 if ((this.Options & (TaskCreationOptions)InternalTaskOptions.PromiseTask) != 0 &&
 14662                    !(this is ITaskCompletionAction))
 4663                {
 14664                    var etwLog = TplEtwProvider.Log;
 14665                     if (etwLog.IsEnabled())
 4666                    {
 04667                         etwLog.AwaitTaskContinuationScheduled(TaskScheduler.Current.Id, Task.CurrentId ?? 0, continuatio
 4668                    }
 4669                }
 4670
 4671                // Attempt to enqueue the continuation
 14672                bool continuationQueued = AddTaskContinuation(continuation, addBeforeOthers: false);
 4673
 4674                // If the continuation was not queued (because the task completed), then run it now.
 24675                 if (!continuationQueued) continuation.Run(this, bCanInlineContinuationTask: true);
 4676            }
 14677        }
 4678        #endregion

 4690        private void AddCompletionAction(ITaskCompletionAction action, bool addBeforeOthers)
 4691        {
 14692             if (!AddTaskContinuation(action, addBeforeOthers))
 14693                action.Invoke(this); // run the action directly if we failed to queue the continuation (i.e., the task c
 14694        }
 4695
 4696        // Support method for AddTaskContinuation that takes care of multi-continuation logic.
 4697        // Returns true if and only if the continuation was successfully queued.
 4698        // THIS METHOD ASSUMES THAT m_continuationObject IS NOT NULL.  That case was taken
 4699        // care of in the calling method, AddTaskContinuation().
 4700        private bool AddTaskContinuationComplex(object tc, bool addBeforeOthers)
 4701        {
 4702            Contract.Requires(tc != null, "Expected non-null tc object in AddTaskContinuationComplex");
 4703
 14704            object oldValue = m_continuationObject;
 4705
 4706            // Logic for the case where we were previously storing a single continuation
 14707             if ((oldValue != s_taskCompletionSentinel) && (!(oldValue is List<object>)))
 4708            {
 4709                // Construct a new TaskContinuation list
 14710                List<object> newList = new List<object>();
 4711
 4712                // Add in the old single value
 14713                newList.Add(oldValue);
 4714
 4715                // Now CAS in the new list
 14716                Interlocked.CompareExchange(ref m_continuationObject, newList, oldValue);
 4717
 4718                // We might be racing against another thread converting the single into
 4719                // a list, or we might be racing against task completion, so resample "list"
 4720                // below.
 4721            }
 4722
 4723            // m_continuationObject is guaranteed at this point to be either a List or
 4724            // s_taskCompletionSentinel.
 14725            List<object> list = m_continuationObject as List<object>;
 14726             Contract.Assert((list != null) || (m_continuationObject == s_taskCompletionSentinel),
 14727                "Expected m_continuationObject to be list or sentinel");
 4728
 4729            // If list is null, it can only mean that s_taskCompletionSentinel has been exchanged
 4730            // into m_continuationObject.  Thus, the task has completed and we should return false
 4731            // from this method, as we will not be queuing up the continuation.
 14732             if (list != null)
 4733            {
 14734                lock (list)
 4735                {
 4736                    // It is possible for the task to complete right after we snap the copy of
 4737                    // the list.  If so, then fall through and return false without queuing the
 4738                    // continuation.
 14739                     if (m_continuationObject != s_taskCompletionSentinel)
 4740                    {
 4741                        // Before growing the list we remove possible null entries that are the
 4742                        // result from RemoveContinuations()
 14743                         if (list.Count == list.Capacity)
 4744                        {
 14745                            list.RemoveAll(s_IsTaskContinuationNullPredicate);
 4746                        }
 4747
 14748                         if (addBeforeOthers)
 14749                            list.Insert(0, tc);
 4750                        else
 14751                            list.Add(tc);
 4752
 14753                        return true; // continuation successfully queued, so return true.
 4754                    }
 04755                }
 4756            }
 4757
 4758            // We didn't succeed in queuing the continuation, so return false.
 14759            return false;
 14760        }
 4761
 4762        // Record a continuation task or action.
 4763        // Return true if and only if we successfully queued a continuation.
 4764        private bool AddTaskContinuation(object tc, bool addBeforeOthers)
 4765        {
 4766            Contract.Requires(tc != null);
 4767
 4768            // Make sure that, if someone calls ContinueWith() right after waiting for the predecessor to complete,
 4769            // we don't queue up a continuation.
 24770             if (IsCompleted) return false;
 4771
 4772            // Try to just jam tc into m_continuationObject
 14773             if ((m_continuationObject != null) || (Interlocked.CompareExchange(ref m_continuationObject, tc, null) != nu
 4774            {
 4775                // If we get here, it means that we failed to CAS tc into m_continuationObject.
 4776                // Therefore, we must go the more complicated route.
 14777                return AddTaskContinuationComplex(tc, addBeforeOthers);
 4778            }
 14779            else return true;
 4780        }

 4782        // Removes a continuation task from m_continuations
 4783        internal void RemoveContinuation(object continuationObject) // could be TaskContinuation or Action<Task>
 4784        {
 4785            // We need to snap a local reference to m_continuations since reading a volatile object is more costly.
 4786            // Also to prevent the value to be changed as result of a race condition with another method.
 14787            object continuationsLocalRef = m_continuationObject;
 4788
 4789            // Task is completed. Nothing to do here.
 24790             if (continuationsLocalRef == s_taskCompletionSentinel) return;
 4791
 14792            List<object> continuationsLocalListRef = continuationsLocalRef as List<object>;
 4793
 14794             if (continuationsLocalListRef == null)
 4795            {
 4796                // This is not a list. If we have a single object (the one we want to remove) we try to replace it with 
 4797                // Note we cannot go back to a null state, since it will mess up the AddTaskContinuation logic.
 14798                 if (Interlocked.CompareExchange(ref m_continuationObject, new List<object>(), continuationObject) != con
 4799                {
 4800                    // If we fail it means that either AddContinuationComplex won the race condition and m_continuationO
 4801                    // that contains the element we want to remove. Or FinishContinuations set the s_taskCompletionSenti
 4802                    // So we should try to get a list one more time
 14803                    continuationsLocalListRef = m_continuationObject as List<object>;
 14804                }
 4805                else
 4806                {
 4807                    // Exchange was successful so we can skip the last comparison
 14808                    return;
 4809                }
 4810            }
 4811
 4812            // if continuationsLocalRef == null it means s_taskCompletionSentinel has been set already and there is noth
 14813             if (continuationsLocalListRef != null)
 4814            {
 14815                lock (continuationsLocalListRef)
 4816                {
 4817                    // There is a small chance that this task completed since we took a local snapshot into
 4818                    // continuationsLocalRef.  In that case, just return; we don't want to be manipulating the
 4819                    // continuation list as it is being processed.
 14820                     if (m_continuationObject == s_taskCompletionSentinel) return;
 4821
 4822                    // Find continuationObject in the continuation list
 14823                    int index = continuationsLocalListRef.IndexOf(continuationObject);
 4824
 14825                     if (index != -1)
 4826                    {
 4827                        // null out that TaskContinuation entry, which will be interpreted as "to be cleaned up"
 14828                        continuationsLocalListRef[index] = null;
 4829
 4830                    }
 14831                }
 4832            }
 14833        }
 4834

 14836        private readonly static Predicate<object> s_IsTaskContinuationNullPredicate =

 4979        /// <summary>
 4980        /// Waits for all of the provided <see cref="Task"/> objects to complete execution.
 4981        /// </summary>
 4982        /// <returns>
 4983        /// true if all of the <see cref="Task"/> instances completed execution within the allotted time;
 4984        /// otherwise, false.
 4985        /// </returns>
 4986        /// <param name="tasks">
 4987        /// An array of <see cref="Task"/> instances on which to wait.
 4988        /// </param>
 4989        /// <param name="millisecondsTimeout">
 4990        /// The number of milliseconds to wait, or <see cref="System.Threading.Timeout.Infinite"/> (-1) to
 4991        /// wait indefinitely.
 4992        /// </param>
 4993        /// <param name="cancellationToken">
 4994        /// A <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to observe while waiting for the tasks to complete.
 4995        /// </param>
 4996        /// <exception cref="T:System.ArgumentNullException">
 4997        /// The <paramref name="tasks"/> argument is null.
 4998        /// </exception>
 4999        /// <exception cref="T:System.ArgumentException">
 5000        /// The <paramref name="tasks"/> argument contains a null element.
 5001        /// </exception>
 5002        /// <exception cref="T:System.AggregateException">
 5003        /// At least one of the <see cref="Task"/> instances was canceled -or- an exception was thrown during
 5004        /// the execution of at least one of the <see cref="Task"/> instances.
 5005        /// </exception>
 5006        /// <exception cref="T:System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException">
 5007        /// <paramref name="millisecondsTimeout"/> is a negative number other than -1, which represents an
 5008        /// infinite time-out.
 5009        /// </exception>
 5010        /// <exception cref="T:System.OperationCanceledException">
 5011        /// The <paramref name="cancellationToken"/> was canceled.
 5012        /// </exception>
 5013        [MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.NoOptimization)]  // this is needed for the parallel debugger
 5014        public static bool WaitAll(Task[] tasks, int millisecondsTimeout, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
 5015        {
 15016             if (tasks == null)
 5017            {
 05018                throw new ArgumentNullException("tasks");
 5019            }
 15020             if (millisecondsTimeout < -1)
 5021            {
 05022                throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException("millisecondsTimeout");
 5023            }
 5024            Contract.EndContractBlock();
 5025
 15026            cancellationToken.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // early check before we make any allocations
 5027
 5028            //
 5029            // In this WaitAll() implementation we have 2 alternate code paths for a task to be handled:
 5030            // CODEPATH1: skip an already completed task, CODEPATH2: actually wait on tasks
 5031            // We make sure that the exception behavior of Task.Wait() is replicated the same for tasks handled in eithe
 5032            //
 5033
 15034            List<Exception> exceptions = null;
 15035            List<Task> waitedOnTaskList = null;
 15036            List<Task> notificationTasks = null;
 5037
 5038            // If any of the waited-upon tasks end as Faulted or Canceled, set these to true.
 25039            bool exceptionSeen = false, cancellationSeen = false;
 5040
 15041            bool returnValue = true;
 5042
 5043            // Collects incomplete tasks in "waitedOnTaskList"
 35044             for (int i = tasks.Length - 1; i >= 0; i--)
 5045            {
 15046                Task task = tasks[i];
 5047
 15048                 if (task == null)
 5049                {
 05050                    throw new ArgumentException(Environment.GetResourceString("Task_WaitMulti_NullTask"), "tasks");
 5051                }
 5052
 15053                bool taskIsCompleted = task.IsCompleted;
 15054                 if (!taskIsCompleted)
 5055                {
 5056                    // try inlining the task only if we have an infinite timeout and an empty cancellation token
 15057                     if (millisecondsTimeout != Timeout.Infinite || cancellationToken.CanBeCanceled)
 5058                    {
 5059                        // We either didn't attempt inline execution because we had a non-infinite timeout or we had a c
 5060                        // In all cases we need to do a full wait on the task (=> add its event into the list.)
 15061                        AddToList(task, ref waitedOnTaskList, initSize: tasks.Length);
 15062                    }
 5063                    else
 5064                    {
 5065                        // We are eligible for inlining.  If it doesn't work, we'll do a full wait.
 15066                         taskIsCompleted = task.WrappedTryRunInline() && task.IsCompleted; // A successful TryRunInline d
 25067                         if (!taskIsCompleted) AddToList(task, ref waitedOnTaskList, initSize: tasks.Length);
 5068                    }
 5069                }
 5070
 15071                 if (taskIsCompleted)
 5072                {
 15073                     if (task.IsFaulted) exceptionSeen = true;
 25074                     else if (task.IsCanceled) cancellationSeen = true;
 15075                     if (task.IsWaitNotificationEnabled) AddToList(task, ref notificationTasks, initSize: 1);
 5076                }
 5077            }
 5078
 15079             if (waitedOnTaskList != null)
 5080            {
 5081                // Block waiting for the tasks to complete.
 15082                returnValue = WaitAllBlockingCore(waitedOnTaskList, millisecondsTimeout, cancellationToken);
 5083
 5084                // If the wait didn't time out, ensure exceptions are propagated, and if a debugger is
 5085                // attached and one of these tasks requires it, that we notify the debugger of a wait completion.
 15086                 if (returnValue)
 5087                {
 5088                    // Add any exceptions for this task to the collection, and if it's wait
 5089                    // notification bit is set, store it to operate on at the end.
 35090                     foreach (var task in waitedOnTaskList)
 5091                    {
 15092                         if (task.IsFaulted) exceptionSeen = true;
 25093                         else if (task.IsCanceled) cancellationSeen = true;
 15094                         if (task.IsWaitNotificationEnabled) AddToList(task, ref notificationTasks, initSize: 1);
 5095                    }
 5096                }
 5097
 5098                // We need to prevent the tasks array from being GC'ed until we come out of the wait.
 5099                // This is necessary so that the Parallel Debugger can traverse it during the long wait and
 5100                // deduce waiter/waitee relationships
 15101                GC.KeepAlive(tasks);
 5102            }
 5103
 5104            // Now that we're done and about to exit, if the wait completed and if we have
 5105            // any tasks with a notification bit set, signal the debugger if any requires it.
 15106             if (returnValue && notificationTasks != null)
 5107            {
 5108                // Loop through each task tha that had its bit set, and notify the debugger
 5109                // about the first one that requires it.  The debugger will reset the bit
 5110                // for any tasks we don't notify of as soon as we break, so we only need to notify
 5111                // for one.
 05112                 foreach (var task in notificationTasks)
 5113                {
 05114                     if (task.NotifyDebuggerOfWaitCompletionIfNecessary()) break;
 5115                }
 5116            }
 5117
 5118            // If one or more threw exceptions, aggregate and throw them.
 15119             if (returnValue && (exceptionSeen || cancellationSeen))
 5120            {
 5121                // If the WaitAll was canceled and tasks were canceled but not faulted,
 5122                // prioritize throwing an OCE for canceling the WaitAll over throwing an
 5123                // AggregateException for all of the canceled Tasks.  This helps
 5124                // to bring determinism to an otherwise non-determistic case of using
 5125                // the same token to cancel both the WaitAll and the Tasks.
 25126                 if (!exceptionSeen) cancellationToken.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
 5127
 5128                // Now gather up and throw all of the exceptions.
 45129                 foreach (var task in tasks) AddExceptionsForCompletedTask(ref exceptions, task);
 15130                Contract.Assert(exceptions != null, "Should have seen at least one exception");
 15131                throw new AggregateException(exceptions);
 5132            }
 5133
 15134            return returnValue;
 5135        }
 5136
 5137        /// <summary>Adds an element to the list, initializing the list if it's null.</summary>
 5138        /// <typeparam name="T">Specifies the type of data stored in the list.</typeparam>
 5139        /// <param name="item">The item to add.</param>
 5140        /// <param name="list">The list.</param>
 5141        /// <param name="initSize">The size to which to initialize the list if the list is null.</param>
 5142        private static void AddToList<T>(T item, ref List<T> list, int initSize)
 5143        {
 25144             if (list == null) list = new List<T>(initSize);
 15145            list.Add(item);
 15146        }
 5147
 5148        /// <summary>Performs a blocking WaitAll on the vetted list of tasks.</summary>
 5149        /// <param name="tasks">The tasks, which have already been checked and filtered for completion.</param>
 5150        /// <param name="millisecondsTimeout">The timeout.</param>
 5151        /// <param name="cancellationToken">The cancellation token.</param>
 5152        /// <returns>true if all of the tasks completed; otherwise, false.</returns>
 5153        private static bool WaitAllBlockingCore(List<Task> tasks, int millisecondsTimeout, CancellationToken cancellatio
 5154        {
 15155            Contract.Assert(tasks != null, "Expected a non-null list of tasks");
 15156            Contract.Assert(tasks.Count > 0, "Expected at least one task");
 5157
 15158            bool waitCompleted = false;
 15159            var mres = new SetOnCountdownMres(tasks.Count);
 5160            try
 5161            {
 35162                 foreach (var task in tasks)
 5163                {
 15164                    task.AddCompletionAction(mres, addBeforeOthers: true);
 5165                }
 15166                waitCompleted = mres.Wait(millisecondsTimeout, cancellationToken);
 15167            }
 5168            finally
 5169            {
 15170                 if (!waitCompleted)
 5171                {
 35172                     foreach (var task in tasks)
 5173                    {
 25174                         if (!task.IsCompleted) task.RemoveContinuation(mres);
 5175                    }
 5176                }
 5177                // It's ok that we don't dispose of the MRES here, as we never
 5178                // access the MRES' WaitHandle, and thus no finalizable resources
 5179                // are actually created.  We don't always just Dispose it because
 5180                // a continuation that's accessing the MRES could still be executing.
 15181            }
 15182            return waitCompleted;
 5183        }
 5184
 5185        // A ManualResetEventSlim that will get Set after Invoke is called count times.
 5186        // This allows us to replace this logic:
 5187        //      var mres = new ManualResetEventSlim(tasks.Count);
 5188        //      Action<Task> completionAction = delegate { if(Interlocked.Decrement(ref count) == 0) mres.Set(); };
 5189        //      foreach(var task in tasks) task.AddCompletionAction(completionAction);
 5190        // with this logic:
 5191        //      var mres = new SetOnCountdownMres(tasks.Count);
 5192        //      foreach(var task in tasks) task.AddCompletionAction(mres);
 5193        // which saves a couple of allocations.
 5194        //
 5195        // Used in WaitAllBlockingCore (above).
 5196        private sealed class SetOnCountdownMres : ManualResetEventSlim, ITaskCompletionAction
 5197        {
 5198            private int _count;
 5199
 15200            internal SetOnCountdownMres(int count)
 5201            {
 15202                Contract.Assert(count > 0, "Expected count > 0");
 15203                _count = count;
 15204            }
 5205
 5206            public void Invoke(Task completingTask)
 5207            {
 25208                 if (Interlocked.Decrement(ref _count) == 0) Set();
 15209                Contract.Assert(_count >= 0, "Count should never go below 0");
 15210            }
 5211        }
 5212
 5213        /// <summary>
 5214        /// Internal WaitAll implementation which is meant to be used with small number of tasks,
 5215        /// optimized for Parallel.Invoke and other structured primitives.
 5216        /// </summary>
 5217        internal static void FastWaitAll(Task[] tasks)
 5218        {
 5219            Contract.Requires(tasks != null);
 5220
 5221            List<Exception> exceptions = null;
 5222
 5223            // Collects incomplete tasks in "waitedOnTaskList" and their cooperative events in "cooperativeEventList"
 5224            for (int i = tasks.Length - 1; i >= 0; i--)
 5225            {
 5226                if (!tasks[i].IsCompleted)
 5227                {
 5228                    // Just attempting to inline here... result doesn't matter.
 5229                    // We'll do a second pass to do actual wait on each task, and to aggregate their exceptions.
 5230                    // If the task is inlined here, it will register as IsCompleted in the second pass
 5231                    // and will just give us the exception.
 5232                    tasks[i].WrappedTryRunInline();
 5233                }
 5234            }
 5235
 5236            // Wait on the tasks.
 5237            for (int i = tasks.Length - 1; i >= 0; i--)
 5238            {
 5239                var task = tasks[i];
 5240                task.SpinThenBlockingWait(Timeout.Infinite, default(CancellationToken));
 5241                AddExceptionsForCompletedTask(ref exceptions, task);
 5242
 5243                // Note that unlike other wait code paths, we do not check
 5244                // task.NotifyDebuggerOfWaitCompletionIfNecessary() here, because this method is currently
 5245                // only used from contexts where the tasks couldn't have that bit set, namely
 5246                // Parallel.Invoke.  If that ever changes, such checks should be added here.
 5247            }
 5248
 5249            // If one or more threw exceptions, aggregate them.
 5250            if (exceptions != null)
 5251            {
 5252                throw new AggregateException(exceptions);
 5253            }
 5254        }
 5255
 5256        /// <summary>
 5257        /// This internal function is only meant to be called by WaitAll()
 5258        /// If the completed task is canceled or it has other exceptions, here we will add those
 5259        /// into the passed in exception list (which will be lazily initialized here).
 5260        /// </summary>
 5261        internal static void AddExceptionsForCompletedTask(ref List<Exception> exceptions, Task t)
 5262        {
 15263            AggregateException ex = t.GetExceptions(true);
 15264             if (ex != null)
 5265            {
 5266                // make sure the task's exception observed status is set appropriately
 5267                // it's possible that WaitAll was called by the parent of an attached child,
 5268                // this will make sure it won't throw again in the implicit wait
 15269                t.UpdateExceptionObservedStatus();
 5270
 15271                 if (exceptions == null)
 5272                {
 15273                    exceptions = new List<Exception>(ex.InnerExceptions.Count);
 5274                }
 5275
 15276                exceptions.AddRange(ex.InnerExceptions);
 5277            }
 15278        }

 5281        /// <summary>
 5282        /// Waits for any of the provided <see cref="Task"/> objects to complete execution.
 5283        /// </summary>
 5284        /// <param name="tasks">
 5285        /// An array of <see cref="Task"/> instances on which to wait.
 5286        /// </param>
 5287        /// <returns>The index of the completed task in the <paramref name="tasks"/> array argument.</returns>
 5288        /// <exception cref="T:System.ArgumentNullException">
 5289        /// The <paramref name="tasks"/> argument is null.
 5290        /// </exception>
 5291        /// <exception cref="T:System.ArgumentException">
 5292        /// The <paramref name="tasks"/> argument contains a null element.
 5293        /// </exception>
 5294        [MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.NoOptimization)]  // this is needed for the parallel debugger
 5295        public static int WaitAny(params Task[] tasks)

 15297            int waitResult = WaitAny(tasks, Timeout.Infinite);

 15333                throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException("timeout");
 5334            }
 5335

 5337        }

 5396        /// <summary>
 5397        /// Waits for any of the provided <see cref="Task"/> objects to complete execution.
 5398        /// </summary>
 5399        /// <param name="tasks">
 5400        /// An array of <see cref="Task"/> instances on which to wait.
 5401        /// </param>
 5402        /// <param name="millisecondsTimeout">
 5403        /// The number of milliseconds to wait, or <see cref="System.Threading.Timeout.Infinite"/> (-1) to
 5404        /// wait indefinitely.
 5405        /// </param>
 5406        /// <param name="cancellationToken">
 5407        /// A <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to observe while waiting for a task to complete.
 5408        /// </param>
 5409        /// <returns>
 5410        /// The index of the completed task in the <paramref name="tasks"/> array argument, or -1 if the
 5411        /// timeout occurred.
 5412        /// </returns>
 5413        /// <exception cref="T:System.ArgumentNullException">
 5414        /// The <paramref name="tasks"/> argument is null.
 5415        /// </exception>
 5416        /// <exception cref="T:System.ArgumentException">
 5417        /// The <paramref name="tasks"/> argument contains a null element.
 5418        /// </exception>
 5419        /// <exception cref="T:System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException">
 5420        /// <paramref name="millisecondsTimeout"/> is a negative number other than -1, which represents an
 5421        /// infinite time-out.
 5422        /// </exception>
 5423        /// <exception cref="T:System.OperationCanceledException">
 5424        /// The <paramref name="cancellationToken"/> was canceled.
 5425        /// </exception>
 5426        [MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.NoOptimization)]  // this is needed for the parallel debugger
 5427        public static int WaitAny(Task[] tasks, int millisecondsTimeout, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
 5428        {
 15429             if (tasks == null)
 5430            {
 15431                throw new ArgumentNullException("tasks");
 5432            }
 15433             if (millisecondsTimeout < -1)
 5434            {
 15435                throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException("millisecondsTimeout");
 5436            }
 5437            Contract.EndContractBlock();
 5438
 15439            cancellationToken.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // early check before we make any allocations
 5440
 15441            int signaledTaskIndex = -1;
 5442
 5443            // Make a pass through the loop to check for any tasks that may have
 5444            // already been completed, and to verify that no tasks are null.
 5445
 35446             for (int taskIndex = 0; taskIndex < tasks.Length; taskIndex++)
 5447            {
 15448                Task task = tasks[taskIndex];
 5449
 15450                 if (task == null)
 5451                {
 15452                    throw new ArgumentException(Environment.GetResourceString("Task_WaitMulti_NullTask"), "tasks");
 5453                }
 5454
 15455                 if (signaledTaskIndex == -1 && task.IsCompleted)
 5456                {
 5457                    // We found our first completed task.  Store it, but we can't just return here,
 5458                    // as we still need to validate the whole array for nulls.
 15459                    signaledTaskIndex = taskIndex;
 5460                }
 5461            }
 5462
 15463             if (signaledTaskIndex == -1 && tasks.Length != 0)
 5464            {
 15465                Task<Task> firstCompleted = TaskFactory.CommonCWAnyLogic(tasks);
 15466                bool waitCompleted = firstCompleted.Wait(millisecondsTimeout, cancellationToken);
 15467                 if (waitCompleted)
 5468                {
 15469                    Contract.Assert(firstCompleted.Status == TaskStatus.RanToCompletion);
 15470                    signaledTaskIndex = Array.IndexOf(tasks, firstCompleted.Result);
 15471                    Contract.Assert(signaledTaskIndex >= 0);
 5472                }
 5473            }
 5474
 5475            // We need to prevent the tasks array from being GC'ed until we come out of the wait.
 5476            // This is necessary so that the Parallel Debugger can traverse it during the long wait
 5477            // and deduce waiter/waitee relationships
 15478            GC.KeepAlive(tasks);
 5479
 5480            // Return the index
 15481            return signaledTaskIndex;
 5482        }

 5538        /// <summary>Creates a <see cref="Task{TResult}"/> that's completed due to cancellation with the specified token
 5539        /// <typeparam name="TResult">The type of the result returned by the task.</typeparam>

 5775        /// <summary>
 5776        /// Creates a Task that will complete after a time delay.
 5777        /// </summary>
 5778        /// <param name="delay">The time span to wait before completing the returned Task</param>
 5779        /// <param name="cancellationToken">The cancellation token that will be checked prior to completing the returned

 5789        /// Canceled state.  Otherwise, the Task is completed in RanToCompletion state once the specified time
 5790        /// delay has expired.
 5791        /// </remarks>
 5792        public static Task Delay(TimeSpan delay, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
 5793        {
 15794            long totalMilliseconds = (long)delay.TotalMilliseconds;
 15795             if (totalMilliseconds < -1 || totalMilliseconds > Int32.MaxValue)
 5796            {
 15797                throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException("delay", Environment.GetResourceString("Task_Delay_InvalidDelay"))
 5798            }
 5799
 15800            return Delay((int)totalMilliseconds, cancellationToken);
 5801        }

 5803        /// <summary>

 5819        /// <summary>
 5820        /// Creates a Task that will complete after a time delay.
 5821        /// </summary>
 5822        /// <param name="millisecondsDelay">The number of milliseconds to wait before completing the returned Task</para
 5823        /// <param name="cancellationToken">The cancellation token that will be checked prior to completing the returned
 5824        /// <returns>A Task that represents the time delay</returns>
 5825        /// <exception cref="T:System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException">
 5826        /// The <paramref name="millisecondsDelay"/> is less than -1.
 5827        /// </exception>
 5828        /// <exception cref="T:System.ObjectDisposedException">
 5829        /// The provided <paramref name="cancellationToken"/> has already been disposed.
 5830        /// </exception>
 5831        /// <remarks>
 5832        /// If the cancellation token is signaled before the specified time delay, then the Task is completed in
 5833        /// Canceled state.  Otherwise, the Task is completed in RanToCompletion state once the specified time
 5834        /// delay has expired.
 5835        /// </remarks>
 5836        public static Task Delay(int millisecondsDelay, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
 5837        {
 5838            // Throw on non-sensical time
 15839             if (millisecondsDelay < -1)
 5840            {
 15841                throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException("millisecondsDelay", Environment.GetResourceString("Task_Delay_Inv
 5842            }
 5843            Contract.EndContractBlock();
 5844
 5845            // some short-cuts in case quick completion is in order
 15846             if (cancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested)
 5847            {
 5848                // return a Task created as already-Canceled
 15849                return Task.FromCancellation(cancellationToken);
 5850            }
 15851             else if (millisecondsDelay == 0)
 5852            {
 5853                // return a Task created as already-RanToCompletion
 15854                return Task.CompletedTask;
 5855            }
 5856
 5857            // Construct a promise-style Task to encapsulate our return value
 15858            var promise = new DelayPromise(cancellationToken);
 5859
 5860            // Register our cancellation token, if necessary.
 15861             if (cancellationToken.CanBeCanceled)
 5862            {
 25863                 promise.Registration = cancellationToken.InternalRegisterWithoutEC(state => ((DelayPromise)state).Comple
 5864            }
 5865
 5866            // ... and create our timer and make sure that it stays rooted.
 15867             if (millisecondsDelay != Timeout.Infinite) // no need to create the timer if it's an infinite timeout
 5868            {
 25869                 promise.Timer = new Timer(state => ((DelayPromise)state).Complete(), promise, millisecondsDelay, Timeout
 15870                promise.Timer.KeepRootedWhileScheduled();
 5871            }
 5872
 5873            // Return the timer proxy task
 15874            return promise;
 5875        }

 5877        /// <summary>Task that also stores the completion closure and logic for Task.Delay implementation.</summary>
 5878        private sealed class DelayPromise : Task<VoidTaskResult>
 5879        {
 5880            internal DelayPromise(CancellationToken token)
 15881                : base()
 5882            {
 15883                this.Token = token;
 15884                 if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 05885                    AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationCreation(CausalityTraceLevel.Required, this.Id, "Task.Delay", 0);
 5886
 15887                 if (Task.s_asyncDebuggingEnabled)
 5888                {
 05889                    AddToActiveTasks(this);
 5890                }
 15891            }

 5897            internal void Complete()
 5898            {
 5899                // Transition the task to completed.
 5900                bool setSucceeded;
 5901
 15902                 if (Token.IsCancellationRequested)
 5903                {
 15904                    setSucceeded = TrySetCanceled(Token);
 15905                }

 15911                     if (Task.s_asyncDebuggingEnabled)
 5912                    {
 05913                        RemoveFromActiveTasks(this.Id);
 5914                    }
 15915                    setSucceeded = TrySetResult(default(VoidTaskResult));
 5916                }
 5917
 5918                // If we set the value, also clean up.
 15919                 if (setSucceeded)
 5920                {
 25921                     if (Timer != null) Timer.Dispose();
 15922                    Registration.Dispose();
 5923                }
 15924            }

 5929        /// <summary>

 6040        // Some common logic to support WhenAll() methods
 6041        // tasks should be a defensive copy.
 6042        private static Task InternalWhenAll(Task[] tasks)
 6043        {
 6044            Contract.Requires(tasks != null, "Expected a non-null tasks array");
 16045             return (tasks.Length == 0) ? // take shortcut if there are no tasks upon which to wait
 16046                Task.CompletedTask :
 16047                new WhenAllPromise(tasks);
 6048        }
 6049
 6050        // A Task<VoidTaskResult> that gets completed when all of its constituent tasks complete.
 6051        // Completion logic will analyze the antecedents in order to choose completion status.
 6052        // This type allows us to replace this logic:
 6053        //      Task<VoidTaskResult> promise = new Task<VoidTaskResult>(...);
 6054        //      Action<Task> completionAction = delegate { <completion logic>};
 6055        //      TaskFactory.CommonCWAllLogic(tasksCopy).AddCompletionAction(completionAction);
 6056        //      return promise;
 6057        // which involves several allocations, with this logic:
 6058        //      return new WhenAllPromise(tasksCopy);
 6059        // which saves a couple of allocations and enables debugger notification specialization.
 6060        //
 6061        // Used in InternalWhenAll(Task[])
 6062        private sealed class WhenAllPromise : Task<VoidTaskResult>, ITaskCompletionAction
 6063        {
 6064            /// <summary>
 6065            /// Stores all of the constituent tasks.  Tasks clear themselves out of this
 6066            /// array as they complete, but only if they don't have their wait notification bit set.
 6067            /// </summary>
 6068            private readonly Task[] m_tasks;
 6069            /// <summary>The number of tasks remaining to complete.</summary>
 6070            private int m_count;
 6071
 6072            internal WhenAllPromise(Task[] tasks) :
 16073                base()
 6074            {
 6075                Contract.Requires(tasks != null, "Expected a non-null task array");
 6076                Contract.Requires(tasks.Length > 0, "Expected a non-zero length task array");
 6077
 16078                 if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 06079                    AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationCreation(CausalityTraceLevel.Required, this.Id, "Task.WhenAll", 0
 6080
 16081                 if (s_asyncDebuggingEnabled)
 6082                {
 06083                    AddToActiveTasks(this);
 6084                }
 6085
 16086                m_tasks = tasks;
 16087                m_count = tasks.Length;
 6088
 36089                 foreach (var task in tasks)
 6090                {
 26091                     if (task.IsCompleted) this.Invoke(task); // short-circuit the completion action, if possible
 16092                    else task.AddCompletionAction(this); // simple completion action
 6093                }
 16094            }

 6096            public void Invoke(Task completedTask)
 6097            {
 16098                 if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 06099                    AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationRelation(CausalityTraceLevel.Important, this.Id, CausalityRelatio
 6100
 6101                // Decrement the count, and only continue to complete the promise if we're the last one.
 16102                 if (Interlocked.Decrement(ref m_count) == 0)
 6103                {
 6104                    // Set up some accounting variables
 16105                    List<ExceptionDispatchInfo> observedExceptions = null;
 16106                    Task canceledTask = null;
 6107
 6108                    // Loop through antecedents:
 6109                    //   If any one of them faults, the result will be faulted
 6110                    //   If none fault, but at least one is canceled, the result will be canceled
 6111                    //   If none fault or are canceled, then result will be RanToCompletion

 6113                    {
 16114                        var task = m_tasks[i];
 16115                        Contract.Assert(task != null, "Constituent task in WhenAll should never be null");
 6116
 16117                         if (task.IsFaulted)
 6118                        {
 26119                             if (observedExceptions == null) observedExceptions = new List<ExceptionDispatchInfo>();
 16120                            observedExceptions.AddRange(task.GetExceptionDispatchInfos());
 16121                        }
 16122                         else if (task.IsCanceled)
 6123                        {
 26124                             if (canceledTask == null) canceledTask = task; // use the first task that's canceled
 6125                        }
 6126
 6127                        // Regardless of completion state, if the task has its debug bit set, transfer it to the
 6128                        // WhenAll task.  We must do this before we complete the task.
 16129                         if (task.IsWaitNotificationEnabled) this.SetNotificationForWaitCompletion(enabled: true);
 16130                        else m_tasks[i] = null; // avoid holding onto tasks unnecessarily
 6131                    }
 6132
 16133                     if (observedExceptions != null)
 6134                    {
 16135                        Contract.Assert(observedExceptions.Count > 0, "Expected at least one exception");
 6136
 6137                        //We don't need to TraceOperationCompleted here because TrySetException will call Finish and we'
 6138
 16139                        TrySetException(observedExceptions);
 16140                    }
 16141                     else if (canceledTask != null)
 6142                    {
 16143                        TrySetCanceled(canceledTask.CancellationToken, canceledTask.GetCancellationExceptionDispatchInfo
 16144                    }
 6145                    else
 6146                    {
 16147                         if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 06148                            AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationCompletion(CausalityTraceLevel.Required, this.Id, AsyncCa
 6149
 16150                         if (Task.s_asyncDebuggingEnabled)
 6151                        {
 06152                            RemoveFromActiveTasks(this.Id);
 6153                        }
 16154                        TrySetResult(default(VoidTaskResult));
 6155                    }
 6156                }
 16157                Contract.Assert(m_count >= 0, "Count should never go below 0");
 16158            }
 6159
 6160            /// <summary>
 6161            /// Returns whether we should notify the debugger of a wait completion.  This returns

 6282            {

 16284                 if (task == null) throw new ArgumentException(Environment.GetResourceString("Task_MultiTaskContinuation_
 16285                tasksCopy[i] = task;
 6286            }

 16289            return InternalWhenAll<TResult>(tasksCopy);
 6290        }

 6292        // Some common logic to support WhenAll<TResult> methods
 6293        private static Task<TResult[]> InternalWhenAll<TResult>(Task<TResult>[] tasks)
 6294        {
 6295            Contract.Requires(tasks != null, "Expected a non-null tasks array");

 16297                new Task<TResult[]>(false, new TResult[0], TaskCreationOptions.None, default(CancellationToken)) :
 16298                new WhenAllPromise<TResult>(tasks);
 6299        }
 6300
 6301        // A Task<T> that gets completed when all of its constituent tasks complete.
 6302        // Completion logic will analyze the antecedents in order to choose completion status.
 6303        // See comments for non-generic version of WhenAllPromise class.
 6304        //
 6305        // Used in InternalWhenAll<TResult>(Task<TResult>[])
 6306        private sealed class WhenAllPromise<T> : Task<T[]>, ITaskCompletionAction
 6307        {
 6308            /// <summary>
 6309            /// Stores all of the constituent tasks.  Tasks clear themselves out of this
 6310            /// array as they complete, but only if they don't have their wait notification bit set.
 6311            /// </summary>
 6312            private readonly Task<T>[] m_tasks;
 6313            /// <summary>The number of tasks remaining to complete.</summary>
 6314            private int m_count;
 6315
 6316            internal WhenAllPromise(Task<T>[] tasks) :
 16317                base()
 6318            {
 6319                Contract.Requires(tasks != null, "Expected a non-null task array");
 6320                Contract.Requires(tasks.Length > 0, "Expected a non-zero length task array");
 6321
 16322                m_tasks = tasks;
 16323                m_count = tasks.Length;
 6324
 16325                 if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 06326                    AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationCreation(CausalityTraceLevel.Required, this.Id, "Task.WhenAll", 0
 6327
 16328                 if (s_asyncDebuggingEnabled)
 6329                {
 06330                    AddToActiveTasks(this);
 6331                }
 6332
 36333                 foreach (var task in tasks)
 6334                {
 26335                     if (task.IsCompleted) this.Invoke(task); // short-circuit the completion action, if possible
 16336                    else task.AddCompletionAction(this); // simple completion action
 6337                }
 16338            }
 6339
 6340            public void Invoke(Task ignored)
 6341            {
 16342                 if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 06343                    AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationRelation(CausalityTraceLevel.Important, this.Id, CausalityRelatio
 6344
 6345                // Decrement the count, and only continue to complete the promise if we're the last one.
 16346                 if (Interlocked.Decrement(ref m_count) == 0)
 6347                {
 6348                    // Set up some accounting variables
 16349                    T[] results = new T[m_tasks.Length];
 16350                    List<ExceptionDispatchInfo> observedExceptions = null;
 16351                    Task canceledTask = null;
 6352
 6353                    // Loop through antecedents:
 6354                    //   If any one of them faults, the result will be faulted
 6355                    //   If none fault, but at least one is canceled, the result will be canceled
 6356                    //   If none fault or are canceled, then result will be RanToCompletion
 36357                     for (int i = 0; i < m_tasks.Length; i++)
 6358                    {
 16359                        Task<T> task = m_tasks[i];
 16360                        Contract.Assert(task != null, "Constituent task in WhenAll should never be null");
 6361
 16362                         if (task.IsFaulted)
 6363                        {
 26364                             if (observedExceptions == null) observedExceptions = new List<ExceptionDispatchInfo>();
 16365                            observedExceptions.AddRange(task.GetExceptionDispatchInfos());
 16366                        }
 16367                         else if (task.IsCanceled)
 6368                        {
 26369                             if (canceledTask == null) canceledTask = task; // use the first task that's canceled
 16370                        }
 6371                        else
 6372                        {
 16373                            Contract.Assert(task.Status == TaskStatus.RanToCompletion);
 16374                            results[i] = task.GetResultCore(waitCompletionNotification: false); // avoid Result, which w
 6375                        }
 6376
 6377                        // Regardless of completion state, if the task has its debug bit set, transfer it to the
 6378                        // WhenAll task.  We must do this before we complete the task.
 16379                         if (task.IsWaitNotificationEnabled) this.SetNotificationForWaitCompletion(enabled: true);
 16380                        else m_tasks[i] = null; // avoid holding onto tasks unnecessarily
 6381                    }
 6382
 16383                     if (observedExceptions != null)
 6384                    {
 16385                        Contract.Assert(observedExceptions.Count > 0, "Expected at least one exception");
 6386
 6387                        //We don't need to TraceOperationCompleted here because TrySetException will call Finish and we'
 6388
 16389                        TrySetException(observedExceptions);
 16390                    }
 16391                     else if (canceledTask != null)
 6392                    {
 16393                        TrySetCanceled(canceledTask.CancellationToken, canceledTask.GetCancellationExceptionDispatchInfo
 16394                    }
 6395                    else
 6396                    {
 16397                         if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 06398                            AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationCompletion(CausalityTraceLevel.Required, this.Id, AsyncCa
 6399
 16400                         if (Task.s_asyncDebuggingEnabled)
 6401                        {
 06402                            RemoveFromActiveTasks(this.Id);
 6403                        }
 16404                        TrySetResult(results);
 6405                    }
 6406                }
 16407                Contract.Assert(m_count >= 0, "Count should never go below 0");
 16408            }
 6409
 6410            /// <summary>
 6411            /// Returns whether we should notify the debugger of a wait completion.  This returns true

 6571        internal virtual Delegate[] GetDelegateContinuationsForDebugger()
 6572        {
 6573            //Avoid an infinite loop by making sure the continuation object is not a reference to istelf.
 06574             if (this.m_continuationObject != this)
 06575                return GetDelegatesFromContinuationObject(this.m_continuationObject);
 6576            else
 06577                return null;
 6578        }
 6579
 6580        internal static Delegate[] GetDelegatesFromContinuationObject(object continuationObject)
 6581        {
 06582             if (continuationObject != null)
 6583            {
 06584                Action singleAction = continuationObject as Action;
 06585                 if (singleAction != null)
 6586                {
 06587                    return new Delegate[] { AsyncMethodBuilderCore.TryGetStateMachineForDebugger(singleAction) };
 6588                }
 6589
 06590                TaskContinuation taskContinuation = continuationObject as TaskContinuation;
 06591                 if (taskContinuation != null)
 6592                {
 06593                    return taskContinuation.GetDelegateContinuationsForDebugger();
 6594                }
 6595
 06596                Task continuationTask = continuationObject as Task;
 06597                 if (continuationTask != null)
 6598                {
 06599                    Contract.Assert(continuationTask.m_action == null);
 06600                    Delegate[] delegates = continuationTask.GetDelegateContinuationsForDebugger();
 06601                     if (delegates != null)
 06602                        return delegates;
 6603                }
 6604
 6605                //We need this ITaskCompletionAction after the Task because in the case of UnwrapPromise
 6606                //the VS debugger is more interested in the continuation than the internal invoke()
 06607                ITaskCompletionAction singleCompletionAction = continuationObject as ITaskCompletionAction;
 06608                 if (singleCompletionAction != null)
 6609                {
 06610                    return new Delegate[] { new Action<Task>(singleCompletionAction.Invoke) };
 6611                }
 6612
 06613                List<object> continuationList = continuationObject as List<object>;
 06614                 if (continuationList != null)
 6615                {
 06616                    List<Delegate> result = new List<Delegate>();
 06617                     foreach (object obj in continuationList)
 6618                    {
 06619                        var innerDelegates = GetDelegatesFromContinuationObject(obj);
 06620                         if (innerDelegates != null)
 6621                        {
 06622                             foreach (var del in innerDelegates)
 6623                            {
 06624                                 if (del != null)
 06625                                    result.Add(del);
 6626                            }
 6627                        }
 6628                    }
 6629
 06630                    return result.ToArray();
 6631                }
 6632            }
 6633
 06634            return null;
 6635        }

 6681        //
 6682
 6683        [MethodImplAttribute(MethodImplOptions.NoInlining)] // Methods containing StackCrawlMark local var have to be ma
 6684        internal ParallelForReplicatingTask(
 6685            ParallelOptions parallelOptions, Action action, TaskCreationOptions creationOptions, InternalTaskOptions int
 6686            : base(action, null, Task.InternalCurrent, default(CancellationToken), creationOptions, internalOptions | In
 6687        {
 6688            // Compute the down count based on scheduler/DOP info in parallelOptions.
 6689            m_replicationDownCount = parallelOptions.EffectiveMaxConcurrencyLevel;
 6690
 6691            StackCrawlMark stackMark = StackCrawlMark.LookForMyCaller;
 6692            PossiblyCaptureContext(ref stackMark);
 6693        }
 6694
 6695
 6696        // Controls degree of replication.  If downcounter is initialized to -1, then
 6697        // replication will be allowed to "run wild".  Otherwise, this method decrements
 6698        // the downcounter each time it is called, calling false when it is called with
 6699        // a zero downcounter.  This method returning false effectively ends the replication
 6700        // of the associated ParallelForReplicatingTask.
 6701        internal override bool ShouldReplicate()
 6702        {
 6703            if (m_replicationDownCount == -1) return true; // "run wild"
 6704
 6705            if (m_replicationDownCount > 0) // Decrement and return true if not called with 0 downcount
 6706            {
 6707                m_replicationDownCount--;
 6708                return true;
 6709            }
 6710
 6711            return false; // We're done replicating
 6712        }
 6713
 6714        internal override Task CreateReplicaTask(Action<object> taskReplicaDelegate, Object stateObject, Task parentTask
 6715                                            TaskCreationOptions creationOptionsForReplica, InternalTaskOptions internalO
 6716        {
 6717            return new ParallelForReplicaTask(taskReplicaDelegate, stateObject, parentTask, taskScheduler,
 6718                                            creationOptionsForReplica, internalOptionsForReplica);
 6719        }
 6720
 6721
 6722    }

 6767    /// <summary>
 6768    /// Specifies flags that control optional behavior for the creation and execution of tasks.
 6769    /// </summary>
 6770    // NOTE: These options are a subset of TaskContinuationsOptions, thus before adding a flag check it is
 6771    // not already in use.
 6772    [Flags]
 6773    [Serializable]
 6774    public enum TaskCreationOptions
 6775    {
 6776        /// <summary>
 6777        /// Specifies that the default behavior should be used.
 6778        /// </summary>
 6779        None = 0x0,
 6780
 6781        /// <summary>
 6782        /// A hint to a <see cref="System.Threading.Tasks.TaskScheduler">TaskScheduler</see> to schedule a
 6783        /// task in as fair a manner as possible, meaning that tasks scheduled sooner will be more likely to
 6784        /// be run sooner, and tasks scheduled later will be more likely to be run later.
 6785        /// </summary>
 6786        PreferFairness = 0x01,
 6787
 6788        /// <summary>
 6789        /// Specifies that a task will be a long-running, course-grained operation. It provides a hint to the
 6790        /// <see cref="System.Threading.Tasks.TaskScheduler">TaskScheduler</see> that oversubscription may be
 6791        /// warranted.
 6792        /// </summary>
 6793        LongRunning = 0x02,
 6794
 6795        /// <summary>
 6796        /// Specifies that a task is attached to a parent in the task hierarchy.
 6797        /// </summary>
 6798        AttachedToParent = 0x04,
 6799
 6800        /// <summary>
 6801        /// Specifies that an InvalidOperationException will be thrown if an attempt is made to attach a child task to t
 6802        /// </summary>
 6803        DenyChildAttach = 0x08,
 6804
 6805        /// <summary>
 6806        /// Prevents the ambient scheduler from being seen as the current scheduler in the created task.  This means tha
 6807        /// like StartNew or ContinueWith that are performed in the created task will see TaskScheduler.Default as the c
 6808        /// </summary>
 6809        HideScheduler = 0x10,
 6810
 6811        // 0x20 is already being used in TaskContinuationOptions
 6812
 6813        /// <summary>
 6814        /// Forces continuations added to the current task to be executed asynchronously.
 6815        /// This option has precedence over TaskContinuationOptions.ExecuteSynchronously
 6816        /// </summary>
 6817        RunContinuationsAsynchronously = 0x40
 6818    }
