 6948
 6949    /// <summary>
 6950    /// Internal helper class to keep track of stack depth and decide whether we should inline or not.
 6951    /// </summary>
 6952    internal class StackGuard
 6953    {
 6954        // current thread's depth of nested inline task executions
 6955        private int m_inliningDepth = 0;
 6956
 6957        // For relatively small inlining depths we don't want to get into the business of stack probing etc.
 6958        // This clearly leaves a window of opportunity for the user code to SO. However a piece of code
 6959        // that can SO in 20 inlines on a typical 1MB stack size probably needs to be revisited anyway.
 6960        private const int MAX_UNCHECKED_INLINING_DEPTH = 20;
 6961
 6962#if !FEATURE_CORECLR
 6963
 6964        private UInt64 m_lastKnownWatermark;
 6965        private static int s_pageSize;
 6966
 6967        // We are conservative here. We assume that the platform needs a whole 64KB to
 6968        // respond to stack overflow. This means that for very small stacks (e.g. 128KB)
 6969        // we'll fail a lot of stack checks incorrectly.
 6970        private const long STACK_RESERVED_SPACE = 4096 * 16;
 6971
 6972#endif  // !FEATURE_CORECLR
 6973
 6974        /// <summary>
 6975        /// This method needs to be called before attempting inline execution on the current thread.
 6976        /// If false is returned, it means we are too close to the end of the stack and should give up inlining.
 6977        /// Each call to TryBeginInliningScope() that returns true must be matched with a
 6978        /// call to EndInliningScope() regardless of whether inlining actually took place.
 6979        /// </summary>
 6980        [SecuritySafeCritical]
 6981        internal bool TryBeginInliningScope()
 6982        {
 6983            // If we're still under the 'safe' limit we'll just skip the stack probe to save p/invoke calls
 6984            if (m_inliningDepth < MAX_UNCHECKED_INLINING_DEPTH || CheckForSufficientStack())
 6985            {
 6986                m_inliningDepth++;
 6987                return true;
 6988            }
 6989            else
 6990                return false;
 6991        }
 6992
 6993        /// <summary>
 6994        /// This needs to be called once for each previous successful TryBeginInliningScope() call after
 6995        /// inlining related logic runs.
 6996        /// </summary>
 6997        internal void EndInliningScope()
 6998        {
 6999            m_inliningDepth--;
 7000            Contract.Assert(m_inliningDepth >= 0, "Inlining depth count should never go negative.");
 7001
 7002            // do the right thing just in case...
 7003            if (m_inliningDepth < 0) m_inliningDepth = 0;
 7004        }
 7005
 7006        [SecurityCritical]
 7007        private unsafe bool CheckForSufficientStack()
 7008        {
 7009#if FEATURE_CORECLR
 7010            return RuntimeHelpers.TryEnsureSufficientExecutionStack();
 7011#else
 7012            // see if we already have the system page size info recorded
 7013            int pageSize = s_pageSize;
 7014            if (pageSize == 0)
 7015            {
 7016                // If not we need to query it from GetSystemInfo()
 7017                // Note that this happens only once for the process lifetime
 7018                Win32Native.SYSTEM_INFO sysInfo = new Win32Native.SYSTEM_INFO();
 7019                Win32Native.GetSystemInfo(ref sysInfo);
 7020
 7021                s_pageSize = pageSize = sysInfo.dwPageSize;
 7022            }
 7023
 7024            Win32Native.MEMORY_BASIC_INFORMATION stackInfo = new Win32Native.MEMORY_BASIC_INFORMATION();
 7025
 7026            // We subtract one page for our request. VirtualQuery rounds UP to the next page.
 7027            // Unfortunately, the stack grows down. If we're on the first page (last page in the
 7028            // VirtualAlloc), we'll be moved to the next page, which is off the stack!
 7029
 7030            UIntPtr currentAddr = new UIntPtr(&stackInfo - pageSize);
 7031            UInt64 current64 = currentAddr.ToUInt64();
 7032
 7033            // Check whether we previously recorded a deeper stack than where we currently are,
 7034            // If so we don't need to do the P/Invoke to VirtualQuery
 7035            if (m_lastKnownWatermark != 0 && current64 > m_lastKnownWatermark)
 7036                return true;
 7037
 7038            // Actual stack probe. P/Invoke to query for the current stack allocation information.
 7039            Win32Native.VirtualQuery(currentAddr.ToPointer(), ref stackInfo, (UIntPtr)(sizeof(Win32Native.MEMORY_BASIC_I
 7040
 7041            // If the current address minus the base (remember: the stack grows downward in the
 7042            // address space) is greater than the number of bytes requested plus the reserved
 7043            // space at the end, the request has succeeded.
 7044
 7045            if ((current64 - ((UIntPtr)stackInfo.AllocationBase).ToUInt64()) > STACK_RESERVED_SPACE)
 7046            {
 7047                m_lastKnownWatermark = current64;
 7048                return true;
 7049            }
 7050
 7051            return false;
 7052#endif
 7053        }
 7054    }
 7055
 7056    // Special internal struct that we use to signify that we are not interested in
 7057    // a Task<VoidTaskResult>'s result.
 7058    internal struct VoidTaskResult { }
 7059
 7060    // Interface to which all completion actions must conform.
 7061    // This interface allows us to combine functionality and reduce allocations.
 7062    // For example, see Task.SetOnInvokeMres, and its use in Task.SpinThenBlockingWait().
 7063    // This code:
 7064    //      ManualResetEvent mres = new ManualResetEventSlim(false, 0);
 7065    //      Action<Task> completionAction = delegate { mres.Set() ; };
 7066    //      AddCompletionAction(completionAction);
 7067    // gets replaced with this:
 7068    //      SetOnInvokeMres mres = new SetOnInvokeMres();
 7069    //      AddCompletionAction(mres);
 7070    // For additional examples of where this is used, see internal classes Task.SignalOnInvokeCDE,
 7071    // Task.WhenAllPromise, Task.WhenAllPromise<T>, TaskFactory.CompleteOnCountdownPromise,
 7072    // TaskFactory.CompleteOnCountdownPromise<T>, and TaskFactory.CompleteOnInvokePromise.
 7073    internal interface ITaskCompletionAction
 7074    {
 7075        void Invoke(Task completingTask);
 7076    }
 7077
 7078    // This class encapsulates all "unwrap" logic, and also implements ITaskCompletionAction,
 7079    // which minimizes the allocations needed for queuing it to its antecedent.  This
 7080    // logic is used by both the Unwrap extension methods and the unwrap-style Task.Run methods.
 7081    internal sealed class UnwrapPromise<TResult> : Task<TResult>, ITaskCompletionAction
 7082    {
 7083        // The possible states for our UnwrapPromise, used by Invoke() to determine which logic to execute
 7084        private const byte STATE_WAITING_ON_OUTER_TASK = 0; // Invoke() means "process completed outer task"
 7085        private const byte STATE_WAITING_ON_INNER_TASK = 1; // Invoke() means "process completed inner task"
 7086        private const byte STATE_DONE = 2;                  // Invoke() means "something went wrong and we are hosed!"
 7087
 7088        // Keep track of our state; initialized to STATE_WAITING_ON_OUTER_TASK in the constructor
 7089        private byte _state;
 7090
 7091        // "Should we check for OperationCanceledExceptions on the outer task and interpret them as proxy cancellation?"
 7092        // Unwrap() sets this to false, Run() sets it to true.
 7093        private readonly bool _lookForOce;
 7094
 7095        public UnwrapPromise(Task outerTask, bool lookForOce)
 7096            : base((object)null, outerTask.CreationOptions & TaskCreationOptions.AttachedToParent)
 7097        {
 7098            Contract.Requires(outerTask != null, "Expected non-null outerTask");
 7099            _lookForOce = lookForOce;
 7100            _state = STATE_WAITING_ON_OUTER_TASK;
 7101
 7102            if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 7103                AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationCreation(CausalityTraceLevel.Required, this.Id, "Task.Unwrap", 0);
 7104
 7105            if (Task.s_asyncDebuggingEnabled)
 7106            {
 7107                AddToActiveTasks(this);
 7108            }
 7109
 7110            // Link ourselves to the outer task.
 7111            // If the outer task has already completed, take the fast path
 7112            // of immediately transferring its results or processing the inner task.
 7113            if (outerTask.IsCompleted)
 7114            {
 7115                ProcessCompletedOuterTask(outerTask);
 7116            }
 7117            else // Otherwise, process its completion asynchronously.
 7118            {
 7119                outerTask.AddCompletionAction(this);
 7120            }
 7121        }
 7122
 7123        // For ITaskCompletionAction
 7124        public void Invoke(Task completingTask)
 7125        {
 7126            // Check the current stack guard.  If we're ok to inline,
 7127            // process the task, and reset the guard when we're done.
 7128            var sg = Task.CurrentStackGuard;
 7129            if (sg.TryBeginInliningScope())
 7130            {
 7131                try { InvokeCore(completingTask); }
 7132                finally { sg.EndInliningScope(); }
 7133            }
 7134            // Otherwise, we're too deep on the stack, and
 7135            // we shouldn't run the continuation chain here, so queue a work
 7136            // item to call back here to Invoke asynchronously.
 7137            else InvokeCoreAsync(completingTask);
 7138        }
 7139
 7140        /// <summary>
 7141        /// Processes the completed task. InvokeCore could be called twice:
 7142        /// once for the outer task, once for the inner task.
 7143        /// </summary>
 7144        /// <param name="completingTask">The completing outer or inner task.</param>
 7145        private void InvokeCore(Task completingTask)
 7146        {
 7147            switch (_state)
 7148            {
 7149                case STATE_WAITING_ON_OUTER_TASK:
 7150                    ProcessCompletedOuterTask(completingTask);
 7151                    // We bump the state inside of ProcessCompletedOuterTask because it can also be called from the cons
 7152                    break;
 7153                case STATE_WAITING_ON_INNER_TASK:
 7154                    bool result = TrySetFromTask(completingTask, lookForOce: false);
 7155                    _state = STATE_DONE; // bump the state
 7156                    Contract.Assert(result, "Expected TrySetFromTask from inner task to succeed");
 7157                    break;
 7158                default:
 7159                    Contract.Assert(false, "UnwrapPromise in illegal state");
 7160                    break;
 7161            }
 7162        }
 7163
 7164        // Calls InvokeCore asynchronously.
 7165        [SecuritySafeCritical]
 7166        private void InvokeCoreAsync(Task completingTask)
 7167        {
 7168            // Queue a call to Invoke.  If we're so deep on the stack that we're at risk of overflowing,
 7169            // there's a high liklihood this thread is going to be doing lots more work before
 7170            // returning to the thread pool (at the very least unwinding through thousands of
 7171            // stack frames).  So we queue to the global queue.
 7172            ThreadPool.UnsafeQueueUserWorkItem(state =>
 7173            {
 7174                // InvokeCore(completingTask);
 7175                var tuple = (Tuple<UnwrapPromise<TResult>, Task>)state;
 7176                tuple.Item1.InvokeCore(tuple.Item2);
 7177            }, Tuple.Create<UnwrapPromise<TResult>, Task>(this, completingTask));
 7178        }
 7179
 7180        /// <summary>Processes the outer task once it's completed.</summary>
 7181        /// <param name="task">The now-completed outer task.</param>
 7182        private void ProcessCompletedOuterTask(Task task)
 7183        {
 7184            Contract.Requires(task != null && task.IsCompleted, "Expected non-null, completed outer task");
 7185            Contract.Assert(_state == STATE_WAITING_ON_OUTER_TASK, "We're in the wrong state!");
 7186
 7187            // Bump our state before proceeding any further
 7188            _state = STATE_WAITING_ON_INNER_TASK;
 7189
 7190            switch (task.Status)
 7191            {
 7192                // If the outer task did not complete successfully, then record the
 7193                // cancellation/fault information to tcs.Task.
 7194                case TaskStatus.Canceled:
 7195                case TaskStatus.Faulted:
 7196                    bool result = TrySetFromTask(task, _lookForOce);
 7197                    Contract.Assert(result, "Expected TrySetFromTask from outer task to succeed");
 7198                    break;
 7199
 7200                // Otherwise, process the inner task it returned.
 7201                case TaskStatus.RanToCompletion:
 7202                    var taskOfTaskOfTResult = task as Task<Task<TResult>>; // it's either a Task<Task> or Task<Task<TRes
 7203                    ProcessInnerTask(taskOfTaskOfTResult != null ?
 7204                        taskOfTaskOfTResult.Result : ((Task<Task>)task).Result);
 7205                    break;
 7206            }
 7207        }
 7208
 7209        /// <summary>Transfer the completion status from "task" to ourself.</summary>
 7210        /// <param name="task">The source task whose results should be transfered to <paramref name="promise"/>.</param>
 7211        /// <param name="lookForOce">Whether or not to look for OperationCanceledExceptions in task's exceptions if it f
 7212        /// <returns>true if the transfer was successful; otherwise, false.</returns>
 7213        private bool TrySetFromTask(Task task, bool lookForOce)
 7214        {
 7215            Contract.Requires(task != null && task.IsCompleted, "TrySetFromTask: Expected task to have completed.");
 7216
 7217            if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 7218                AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationRelation(CausalityTraceLevel.Important, this.Id, CausalityRelation.Jo
 7219
 7220            bool result = false;
 7221            switch (task.Status)
 7222            {
 7223                case TaskStatus.Canceled:
 7224                    result = TrySetCanceled(task.CancellationToken, task.GetCancellationExceptionDispatchInfo());
 7225                    break;
 7226
 7227                case TaskStatus.Faulted:
 7228                    var edis = task.GetExceptionDispatchInfos();
 7229                    ExceptionDispatchInfo oceEdi;
 7230                    OperationCanceledException oce;
 7231                    if (lookForOce && edis.Count > 0 &&
 7232                        (oceEdi = edis[0]) != null &&
 7233                        (oce = oceEdi.SourceException as OperationCanceledException) != null)
 7234                    {
 7235                        result = TrySetCanceled(oce.CancellationToken, oceEdi);
 7236                    }
 7237                    else
 7238                    {
 7239                        result = TrySetException(edis);
 7240                    }
 7241                    break;
 7242
 7243                case TaskStatus.RanToCompletion:
 7244                    var taskTResult = task as Task<TResult>;
 7245
 7246                    if (AsyncCausalityTracer.LoggingOn)
 7247                        AsyncCausalityTracer.TraceOperationCompletion(CausalityTraceLevel.Required, this.Id, AsyncCausal
 7248
 7249                    if (Task.s_asyncDebuggingEnabled)
 7250                    {
 7251                        RemoveFromActiveTasks(this.Id);
 7252                    }
 7253
 7254                    result = TrySetResult(taskTResult != null ? taskTResult.Result : default(TResult));
 7255                    break;
 7256            }
 7257            return result;
 7258        }
 7259
 7260        /// <summary>
 7261        /// Processes the inner task of a Task{Task} or Task{Task{TResult}},
 7262        /// transferring the appropriate results to ourself.
 7263        /// </summary>
 7264        /// <param name="task">The inner task returned by the task provided by the user.</param>
 7265        private void ProcessInnerTask(Task task)
 7266        {
 7267            // If the inner task is null, the proxy should be canceled.
 7268            if (task == null)
 7269            {
 7270                TrySetCanceled(default(CancellationToken));
 7271                _state = STATE_DONE; // ... and record that we are done
 7272            }
 7273
 7274            // Fast path for if the inner task is already completed
 7275            else if (task.IsCompleted)
 7276            {
 7277                TrySetFromTask(task, lookForOce: false);
 7278                _state = STATE_DONE; // ... and record that we are done
 7279            }
 7280
 7281            // The inner task exists but is not yet complete, so when it does complete,
 7282            // take some action to set our completion state.
 7283            else
 7284            {
 7285                task.AddCompletionAction(this);
 7286                // We'll record that we are done when Invoke() is called.
 7287            }
 7288        }
 7289
 7290    }
